<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Manual"><PMID Version="1">26928749</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2016</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>20</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2016</Year><Month>12</Month><Day>30</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1878-1306</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>46</Volume><Issue>3</Issue><PubDate><Year>2016</Year><Month>May</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>The Veterinary clinics of North America. Small animal practice</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Vet Clin North Am Small Anim Pract</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Musculoskeletal MRI.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>421</StartPage><EndPage>v</EndPage><MedlinePgn>421-51, v</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.cvsm.2015.12.003</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0195-5616(15)00180-1</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>MRI has the unique ability to detect abnormal fluid content, and is therefore unparalleled in its role of detection, diagnosis, prognosis, treatment planning and follow-up evaluation of musculoskeletal disease. MRI in companion animals should be considered in the following circumstances: a definitive diagnosis cannot be made on radiographs; a patient is nonresponsive to medical or surgical therapy; prognostic information is desired; assessing surgical margins and traumatic and/or infectious joint and bone disease; ruling out subtle developmental or early aggressive bone lesions. The MRI features of common disorders affecting the shoulder, elbow, stifle, carpal, and tarsal joints are included in this chapter.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2016 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Sage</LastName><ForeName>Jaime E</ForeName><Initials>JE</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>MRVets, P.C., 1